{"parse":{"title":"Private signal","pageid":29402141,"revid":816541730,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>private signal</b> is a custom-designed <a href=\"/wiki/Flag\" title=\"Flag\">flag</a> used to symbolize and identify the owner of a <a href=\"/wiki/Boat\" title=\"Boat\">boat</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> They generally have a\n<a href=\"/wiki/Swallowtail_(flag)\" title=\"Swallowtail (flag)\">swallowtail</a> shape but may instead be rectangular or sometimes triangular.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Private signal tradition is drawn from <a href=\"/wiki/Heraldry\" title=\"Heraldry\">heraldry</a> but typically does not incorporate intricate designs from a <a href=\"/wiki/Family_crest\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Family crest\">family crest</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Etiquette\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Etiquette</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Etiquette\">Etiquette</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_signal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Etiquette\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A private signal may be hoisted while underway and at anchor, day or night, but not while racing.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Power_boat\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Power boat\">Power boats</a> fly the owners' private signal at the top of the <a href=\"/wiki/Main-mast\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Main-mast\">main-mast</a> head or from a short staff on the bow called a bow staff. On a <a href=\"/wiki/Sailboat\" title=\"Sailboat\">sailboat</a> the private signal is flown using a <a href=\"/wiki/Pig_stick\" title=\"Pig stick\">pig stick</a> hoisted to the top of the <a href=\"/wiki/Main-mast\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Main-mast\">main-mast</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Mizzen-mast\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mizzen-mast\">mizzen-mast</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_signal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>From as far back as 4000 BC, Egyptian captains of the Nile would identify themselves to passing ships by placing a clay figurine atop their ships\u2019 aftermost cabin.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Romans used private signals quite often. At sea off Marseilles in 49 BC, the famous Roman <a href=\"/wiki/Brutus\" title=\"Brutus\">Brutus</a> hoisted his private signal during a battle against the Massilians of Pompeii. Primary documents say the Massilians recognized his \u201cflamboyant\u201d signal, so his ship narrowly escaped being rammed simultaneously by two triremes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the Middle Ages private signals were used extensively at sea. The Bayeux Tapestry of 1150 AD shows \u201cMora,\u201d the ship of William, Duke of Normandy, as it flew a white banner, bordered in blue and bearing a golden cross. Other knights in the tapestry boast their own private signals.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_signal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role=\"navigation\" aria-label=\"Portals\" class=\"noprint portal plainlist tright\" style=\"margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;border:solid #aaa 1px\">\n<ul style=\"display:table;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0.1em;max-width:175px;background:#f9f9f9;font-size:85%;line-height:110%;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold\">\n<li style=\"display:table-row\"><span style=\"display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Yacht_foresail.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Yacht_foresail.svg/24px-Yacht_foresail.svg.png\" width=\"24\" height=\"28\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Yacht_foresail.svg/37px-Yacht_foresail.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Yacht_foresail.svg/49px-Yacht_foresail.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"836\" data-file-height=\"955\" /></a></span><span style=\"display:table-cell;padding:0.2em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em;vertical-align:middle\"><a href=\"/wiki/Portal:Nautical\" title=\"Portal:Nautical\">Nautical portal</a></span></li></ul></div>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Maritime_flag#House_flag\" title=\"Maritime flag\">House Flag</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_signal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Rousmaniere, John (1989). <i>The Annapolis Book of Seamanship</i> (2 ed.). New York: Simon and Schuster. pp.&#160;366, 367. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-67167447-2\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-67167447-2\">978-0-67167447-2</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Annapolis+Book+of+Seamanship&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pages=366%2C+367&amp;rft.edition=2&amp;rft.pub=Simon+and+Schuster&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-67167447-2&amp;rft.aulast=Rousmaniere&amp;rft.aufirst=John&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APrivate+signal\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><i>Chapman Piloting Seamanship and Boat Handling</i>. Hearst Marine Books. 1999. p.&#160;585. <a href=\"/wiki/